\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1406435 RJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 Well we had to do it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10968918 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 After you left school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1406435 RJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 As long as we were at - 'til I got married. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10968918 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 What about your brother, would he have any different jobs to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1406435 RJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 Of course he was more with the horses you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10968918 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 That's what he was doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1406435 RJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 Yes. Yes. But he'd milk in his turn. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10968918 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 Would he fetch water?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1406435 RJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 Well - when - some of us girls were a - away or ill or something like that, yes the serving men 
would fetch them as well, and they used - they used the yoke - do you see, yes, and they - they'd fetch more in one go than we would in two or three do you see. 'Cos - nearly two gallon jacks we were having, jacks were the colour you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10968918 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 How far would you have to go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1406435 RJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 
Well, we were going through - two fields of our own, and the next farm, under the railway bridge and up a little hill to a well. WE had two casks at the far end of the house and two casks down between the barn and the stable. And th
ey would - there was a tap on one but only a - a stopper on the others, do you see, and of course we - we looked at that - it was - we did our washing with that. Our drinking and cooking water was the well water. Yes. Yes, but - we were very short of wate
r
 there, and they sank a well - a winch you call it, at the - corner of the house in the - in the - what you call a cae bach, cae bach there and - they - I don't know what the depth of it was, I don't know, but they connected it to the wash house and we ha
d a pump there. We had a pump outside, but that went into - and it wasn't working, it had now some - interference so they put a new thing - and they put a pump inside. We had a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5642835\charrsid15934717 lo}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 vely bath there, you know, wash up, and this water, then we had a pipe going t
hrough the wall to a large tub. We pumped the water and there's spout here, we pumped like this, we filled that tub - with water. For the cows. For the cows. We couldn't use that water, only for - washing floors or swilling down. Because it was chaelybeat
e
. It was a mineral water, if you boiled it it would go brown, you see. And all the clothes would go brown, you can - you can make a khaki rig-out in no time. You know, but you couldn't use it for that you see because it was - it was water for us do you se
e
. Yes, and the cows when we'd - in the winter now, you wouldn't - we had to carry water for the cows to the manager, we'd send the cows out so as to clean the byres I would like to say then turn - turn - and hoping that they'd go and drink the water. They
 
wouldn't drink a drop. They'd come in, they'd go. And we'd pass - we - we'd pump water, they'd drink - no end of that. They'd drink two or three buckets of that. The cows loved it and I think they were in good fettle, you see, it was good water for them y
ou see, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10968918 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 How many cows would you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1406435 RJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 
About the sixteen - milking cows, yes. And we used to rear at least four to six calves a year. Yes. And we kept chickens and ducks. And there was one period I wasn't too good in health, when I was about
 sixteen, seventeen, eighteen - you - I didn't know what was wrong but the doctor told me that I had to - sleep out if possible. But I didn't sleep out, I was too afraid, but I lived out nearly then, and I did an awful lot of outside work in the farm.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10968918 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 You were all right then?
