Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Yes, in his - in its turn. In his time. And hay - of course. And - many a - I was going to say - he had one field there, it was all - we remember it
 all hay. Well in a year or two he'd plough it all, do you see, and it was a lovely old farm - for mushrooms. Oh beautiful mushrooms there. I remember father - ploughed it up and grew potatoes and Swedes and mangels, and we'd go out of a morning with a ba
s
ket and we'd pick a basketful of mushrooms between the rows of potatoes do you see. Yes. Yes, and - of course we were a - a sort of farm - that we was - could - producing our own, in everything, yes, and then - I remember - when I was - well before I was 
m
arried see, about the twenty-one I could have been - I - we used to keep a lot of pigs, remember rearing pigs there. And - and feeding them. Selling them - we used to have a butcher - butcher coming to kill them there do you see. And - sometimes when - ev
e
n - we'd have a - a - a boy now, well - fattened him, because - we - I don't know what was in the ground of the farm but we buy - whether it was - the ground where we bought the bull from - my father used to buy the bulls from a farm in Aberdare, and it w
as pedigree stock do you see, bring it down. But those bulls always went - fierce and savage. We had to get rid of them. After about two years we had to get rid of them.
\par 
