Yes, as soon as we had the outing, we - I remember we - I remember the time we had first outings, because it was - a tea party we used to have - on our fields, we had a tea party in chapel, long tables. My mother kep
t the cloths, then we - we had long cloths, and then we lent our dishes. The horse and trap put it with dishes you see and - and then everybody gave - the food. And my aunt in the small farm, she used to bring teisen lap. You know teisen lap. Oh, slabs of
 
tiesen lap, and mother'd make loaf cake. Then - Auntie Maes mawr would make a good jarful of stewed rhubarb, and bring a jug of cream. And now that with bread and butter. It was gorgeous. Yes. Then after the tea party, we'd come down into our fields, and 
w
e'd usually ask - I remember them asking the ice cream man to come, there'd be a tea party, then he'd come in the field. You'd give him standing rooms here, and then they'd may be buy a box or two of sweets, and they'd throw them, catch them, that's - and
 nuts we used to have after.
