I was in Hawthorn school. That would be - I wasn't eleven, and I'll tell you who played for me. This is interesting, was Morfudd Owen. Morfudd Owen - played for me. Yes. Yes. Oh her - she was a beauty - you didn't - never - know -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10968918 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 She died young didn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1406435 RJ  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14815767\charrsid15934717 
Twenty-seven. Yes. Yes, they're marvellous, yes. And - I'll tell you another thing, when we got on with the - with the music world, it was my husband - she went to 
first - her father was - oh no, no, no, no, it - I'm the wrong one now, I've got the wrong one, not - it was Gwyneth - Gwyneth Pearce, Gwyneth Lewis, do you remember Gwyneth Lewis with the - winning - the Snowflakes - in the National? Well it was my - to 
my husband she came for music first, then he said, well I've taken as long - as far as I can, you'd better let her go to somebody else. That was Gwyneth Lewis but Morfudd Owen we're talking about now.
